thread.title: The Harrisons: Rob Ryan flops in town where his dad shined

title: The Harrisons: Rob Ryan flops in town where his dad shined
text:
In honor of Pittsburgh Steelers linebacker James Harrison's bold stance , our weekly award for NFL players and coaches who didn't even deserve a participation trophy in Week 5. NICK FOLES
On a day when Aaron Rodgers (two INTs) seemed almost human and Todd Gurley gave him 159 rushing yards, the St. Louis quarterback can’t throw four interceptions and think he can win in Green Bay — or anywhere. It’s not a good look for someone the Rams traded for and paid to be their QB of the future.
JAGUARS OFFENSIVE LINE
It allowed Blake Bortles to be sacked six times and opened holes just big enough for the running backs to find 55 yards against a woeful Bucs defense. Sorry, no trophy for any of you. We wouldn't have even give you a ride back to Jacksonville.
ROB RYAN
The Saints defensive coordinator was just what Chip Kelly’s offense needed. The Eagles had been stumbling and bumbling for four weeks but rolled up 519 yards Sunday. And to think Ryan's troops put on that kind of performance in the town where his dad had assembled one of the best defenses in league history.
MATTHEW STAFFORD
Things are unraveling quickly in Detroit. He threw two interceptions before people dug into their popcorn and added a third for good measure. That was enough for Jim Caldwell to bench his quarterback. If we had given Stafford a participation trophy, he would just have thrown it to the Cardinals anyway.
CARY WILLIAMS
The Seahawks cornerback was high-fiving teammates when he thought the Bengals had committed offensive pass interference on a key fourth quarter drive. But the penalty was on Williams. Awkward. Even more awkward when the coaches had to change the whole coverage scheme because he couldn’t guard A.J. Green.
